For monthly data prior to January 2008, please see archived table 25-10-0048. For current monthly data on production and exports of coal, see also table 25-10-0046.
Coal coke is a hard, porous product made from baking bituminous coal in ovens at high temperature. Often used as a fuel and a reducing agent in smelting iron in a blast furnace.
All coal coke plants in Canada are located in Ontario.
Supply of coal to coke plants is determined by the sum of coal stock opening plus coal received plus inventory adjustments minus coal stock closing.
Coal and coal coke received includes Canadian and foreign sources.
Disposition of coal by coke plants is determined by the sum of coal charged to ovens plus coal sold or used for other purposes.
Sold or used for other purposes includes washer losses.
Supply of coal coke is determined by the sum of coal coke stock opening plus coal coke production plus coal coke received plus coal coke adjustments minus coal coke stock closing.

Disposition of coal coke is determined by the sum of coal coke used in blast furnaces plus coal coke used in associated works plus coal coke sold for industrial use plus coal coke sold for export plus coal coke all other sales and/or uses.
